---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'How do I sort lines of text alphabetically online?', a: 'Paste your text into TextWonder\'s Sort Lines tool and it instantly sorts all lines alphabetically (A–Z). You can also sort in reverse (Z–A), numerically, or randomly. Free, no signup.' },
  { q: 'Can I sort lines numerically?', a: 'Yes. TextWonder\'s Sort Lines tool offers numeric sorting, which sorts numbers by value (1, 2, 10, 100) rather than lexicographically (1, 10, 100, 2).' },
  { q: 'How do I sort lines in Excel?', a: 'In Excel, select your column and use Data → Sort. Choose ascending (A–Z) or descending (Z–A). For a single column of text items, select it and sort directly without affecting other columns.' },
  { q: 'How do I sort lines in Notepad++ or VS Code?', a: 'Notepad++: Select all text, then Edit → Line Operations → Sort Lines Lexicographically Ascending. VS Code: There\'s no built-in sort, but the "Sort Lines" extension adds it, or use the command palette with a terminal sort command.' },
  { q: 'What is lexicographic sorting vs natural sorting?', a: 'Lexicographic (alphabetical) sorting compares characters one by one: "10" comes before "9" because "1" < "9". Natural sorting understands numbers: "9" comes before "10". For numbered lists, natural sorting gives more intuitive results.' },
];
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Sort Lines of Text Alphabetically: 4 Methods"
  description="Learn how to sort lines of text alphabetically, numerically, or randomly using free online tools, Excel, Google Sheets, and the command line."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-sort-text-lines"
  date="2025-05-18"
  readTime="4 min read"
  category="Text Formatting"
  faqs={faqs}
>

<p>
  Sorting lines of text is a surprisingly common task: alphabetising bibliography entries, sorting keyword lists for SEO, organising product names, sorting log entries, or just cleaning up a list. Here are four reliable methods.
</p>

<h2>Method 1: Free Online Tool (Instant)</h2>

<p>
  The fastest option for any one-off sorting task:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>Go to <a href="/tools/sort-lines">TextWonder's Sort Lines tool</a>.</li>
  <li>Paste your text (any number of lines).</li>
  <li>Choose: A→Z, Z→A, numeric, or random.</li>
  <li>Copy the sorted output.</li>
</ol>

<p>
  The tool preserves blank lines, handles case-insensitive matching, and works instantly in your browser with no data leaving your device.
</p>

<a href="/tools/sort-lines" class="tool-cta">
  <div class="cta-label">Free Tool</div>
  <div class="cta-title">Sort Lines →</div>
  <div class="cta-desc">Sort any list of lines alphabetically, reverse, numerically, or randomly. Free, instant, browser-based.</div>
</a>

<h2>Method 2: Excel or Google Sheets</h2>

<p>
  If your data is already in a spreadsheet:
</p>

<h3>Excel:</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Select the column containing your lines.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Data</strong> → <strong>Sort</strong>.</li>
  <li>Choose ascending (A–Z) or descending (Z–A).</li>
  <li>If you have other columns, choose whether to expand the selection (sort entire rows) or sort the column only.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Google Sheets:</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Select the column.</li>
  <li>Right-click → <strong>Sort sheet A→Z</strong> (or Z→A).</li>
  <li>Alternatively: <strong>Data</strong> → <strong>Sort range</strong> for more options.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Method 3: Command Line</h2>

<p>
  For large files (thousands or millions of lines), the command line is the most efficient:
</p>

<p><strong>Linux / macOS:</strong></p>
<p><code>sort input.txt &gt; sorted.txt</code> — alphabetical ascending</p>
<p><code>sort -r input.txt &gt; sorted.txt</code> — reverse alphabetical</p>
<p><code>sort -n input.txt &gt; sorted.txt</code> — numeric sort</p>
<p><code>sort -u input.txt &gt; sorted.txt</code> — sort and remove duplicates simultaneously</p>

<p><strong>Windows PowerShell:</strong></p>
<p><code>Get-Content input.txt | Sort-Object | Set-Content sorted.txt</code></p>
<p><code>Get-Content input.txt | Sort-Object -Descending | Set-Content sorted.txt</code></p>

<h2>Method 4: Text Editors</h2>

<p>
  Some text editors have built-in sort functionality:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Notepad++:</strong> Select all → Edit → Line Operations → Sort Lines Lexicographically Ascending/Descending</li>
  <li><strong>Sublime Text:</strong> <code>F9</code> to sort selected lines (requires selecting all first)</li>
  <li><strong>VS Code:</strong> No built-in sort. Install the "Sort Lines" extension or use the terminal.</li>
  <li><strong>Vim:</strong> <code>:sort</code> to sort all lines, <code>:sort!</code> to sort in reverse</li>
</ul>

<h2>Alphabetical vs Numeric Sorting: An Important Difference</h2>

<p>
  Alphabetical (lexicographic) sorting compares character by character. This means <code>10</code> comes before <code>9</code> alphabetically (because "1" &lt; "9"), which is unintuitive when sorting numbers.
</p>

<p>
  For lists containing numbers, always use <strong>numeric sort</strong>:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Alphabetical: 1, 10, 100, 2, 20, 3</li>
  <li>Numeric: 1, 2, 3, 10, 20, 100</li>
</ul>

<p>
  TextWonder's Sort Lines tool offers both options. The command-line <code>sort -n</code> flag enables numeric sorting.
</p>

